The explosion of the COVID-19 has exposed the fact that the American economy, which appears strong in some respects, is deeply flawed, structurally unsound and in need of reform

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
By Jonnes

Editor | Wang Tianni

Sometimes all it takes is a bolt of lightning to see a seemingly healthy tree rotting from the inside. This time, the COVID-19 has revealed that the American economy, which seems strong in some respects, is deeply flawed, structurally unsound and in need of reform.

While the focus in the coming weeks should be on people's health, policy makers should not let this moment pass without an honest discussion of the deep-seated problems in the US economy exposed by the coronavirus crisis.

Over the past decade, the stock market has climbed to all-time highs; Unemployment is at all-time lows; and companies are reporting record profits. But behind this seemingly healthy facade, corruption is spreading.

More and more of the nation's wealth is being seized by the rich and powerful, who use their money and power to ensure that the system continues to serve them. At the same time, the costs of housing, health care, childcare and higher education are rising rapidly while wages for the vast majority of the population are stagnating.

The racial and gender wage and wealth gaps persist and in some cases become even more acute. Special interest groups have succeeded in pushing a deregulatory agenda that shifts risk from companies to taxpayers, and an anti-labour agenda that puts power in the hands of big companies and leaves workers to fend for themselves. Regressive tax policies and short sighted budget decisions have left more than one trillion in the pockets of the rich, while investments in the country's future and those who need it most have been hollowed out.

Many progressives have been talking about this corruption for years. For millions of people who are struggling, this reality is their everyday life. But it wasn't until the possibility of a global public health crisis increased, stock markets plunged, and the problems masked by the shiny veneer of the U.S. economy began to receive more attention. As policymakers intensify their response to the coronavirus, they also need to acknowledge the existence of conservative and austerity policies that have left governments ill equipped to deal with a widespread public health crisis, and make the economy more vulnerable to the coming recession.

The developed country is one of two countries that do not guarantee paid sick leave. Even in the best of times, millions of workers are forced to choose between staying home sick and receiving the salaries they desperately need. Low-income people are the least likely to be on paid sick leave, and they tend to work in occupations that engage with the public: Nursery school teachers, Home Health Aides, restaurant workers and food processors. But as the coronavirus spreads, too many workers will be forced to choose between Three Meals a Day or caring for themselves or their families -- making any outbreak worse.

Similarly, millions of people do not have health insurance. There are also millions of people who do not have adequate insurance and who can not afford to pay out-of-pocket contributions and deductibles when they fall ill. It is already happening that people are being forced to pay thousands of dollars out of their own pockets for coronavirus treatment and testing. Under normal circumstances, the lack or inadequacy of health insurance can be devastating for families, but when people delay treatment or testing for the coronavirus because they can not afford it, the impact on families can be even more severe, deadly, even. This is of particular concern and concern to low income communities, rural areas and the Colored, which already face significant systemic challenges in accessing health care.

If the epidemic worsens, the reality of federal budget decisions will hit people across the country. Even the so-called deficit hawks could join the calls for increased spending on public health, related research and development, and other coronavirus-related activities. But the truth about public health spending is also evident throughout the federal budget: Spending on infrastructure, education and training, social housing and other areas has been underfunded and hollowed out for decades.

Perhaps the result of coronaviruses will be better than many feared. I hope so. Even so, it won't be long before something else happens, cracking open this rotten tree.

A healthy economy is one in which everyone has financial security, a secure network, support and protection to ensure that they can make the right decisions for themselves, for their families, and for their communities. A strong economy is one in which everyone prospers, and wealth and power do not flow only to those who can manipulate the system to their advantage. Only sensible federal investment, an effective federal government, and shared and equitable prosperity can provide such a solid foundation.

A national discussion of the economic realities of most Americans should not be forced by a public health crisis. Unfortunately, this country can not let this crisis pass without facing this problem.

Jonnes is general manager of policy and research for the Groundwork Collaborative.
